---
part: 3
title: "The Chronology and Purpose of Intervention"
slug: "sbi-framework"
---

## Transcript

**Jamie:** Welcome back to Walmart Academy's The Art of Feedback. In our last episode, we talked about the psychology of feedback — how that "personal lens" makes us all react differently to the exact same words. I'm Jamie, and I'm back with our resident leadership strategist, Alex.

**Alex:** Hey, Jamie! Now that we know how feedback is processed in the brain, it's time to talk about the when and the why. Today is all about the chronology and purpose of intervention.

**Jamie:** "Intervention" sounds like a heavy word, but we are really talking about the timing of feedback, right? Why is the clock so critical here?

**Alex:** Because the effectiveness of feedback is intrinsically linked to when you deliver it. Timely feedback matters immensely because it allows leaders to step in while the moment is still highly relevant. If you intervene in real-time, learning can happen instantly. You can clarify assumptions and offer support right then and there.

**Jamie:** So it's not just about reacting faster when things go wrong.

**Alex:** Exactly. The goal isn't merely to react faster to issues; it's to intervene early enough to actively shape outcomes, rather than just measuring them after the fact.

**Jamie:** That's a great distinction — shaping the outcome versus measuring it later. So what does that look like in practice?

**Alex:** It looks like capitalizing on everyday moments. Leaders are presented with so many chances every single day to check in, share their observations, and guide their associates. When you use those real-time moments, it creates a workplace culture where feedback feels completely normal. It becomes entirely supportive and focused on continuous growth, rather than being this intimidating, sweat-inducing event saved for a formal performance review.

**Jamie:** I know what you mean, and in those everyday, real-time moments, what are we actually trying to achieve?

**Alex:** There are really just two primary objectives for giving feedback. First, to redirect behaviors that are starting to drift away from established expectations.

**Jamie:** So, a gentle course correction.

**Alex:** Right. And second, to reinforce the behaviors that are working exceptionally well and driving success. We have to cheerlead the good stuff, too!

**Jamie:** Which is so easy to forget when we are busy putting out everyday fires. We usually only think of feedback as correcting mistakes.

**Alex:** Exactly, but positive reinforcement is arguably just as critical. It actually reminds me of a foundational piece of advice from Sam Walton. Mr. Sam always said: "Appreciate everything your associates do for the business. Nothing else can quite substitute for a few well-chosen, well-timed, sincere words of praise. They're absolutely free and worth a fortune."

**Jamie:** "Free and worth a fortune." I love that so much. And I notice he explicitly calls out that those words need to be well-timed.

**Alex:** He hit the nail on the head. That goes right back to our point about the timeline. Timely, ongoing feedback acts as a safeguard. It helps catch small dips in performance early on to ensure expectations and performance remain perfectly aligned. If you intervene early, the associate can adjust their course while the issue is still completely manageable.

**Jamie:** It prevents a molehill from becoming a mountain. Plus, speaking from an associate's perspective, consistent feedback builds immense trust.

**Alex:** Huge amounts of trust and engagement! Associates understand that their leaders are actually paying close attention and are genuinely invested in their professional growth. It significantly reduces surprises.

**Jamie:** And nobody wants to be surprised at their annual evaluation.

**Alex:** I know I don't. Ongoing guidance makes accountability much easier and paves the way for evaluations to be clearer and fairer. And as Mr. Sam pointed out, it reinforces strengths, too. Early acknowledgment of success encourages continued excellence and really builds an associate's confidence.

**Jamie:** Catch them doing something right, or help them course-correct, and tell them immediately! That's a fantastic framework, Alex. Redirect the drift, reinforce the success, and do it in real-time.

**Alex:** Next time on Walmart Academy's The Art of Feedback, we'll dive into the actual delivery and phrasing of these conversations.
